In the UK the only "treatment" for Nosema that's approved are comb changes (bailey) and then changing floors and crown/cover boards.  No medications are approved. Thymolated  syrup (drenches, sprays and feeds) are used on moderate infections by some beekeepers but they're off-the-radar as far as the NBU/VMD are concerned.  Oxytetracycline is only available via an NBU Bee Inspector and then only for light infection.  Shook swarms are done for moderate and isolated infections - but with heavy infections or an infection that seems to be part of a pocket or outbreak of disease, the infected colonies are culled, frames, excluders and bees incinerated and other parts sterilised (wooden by removing runners and flaming, poly/plastic by bleach immersion and then soda scrubbing.  Euthanizing the colony followed by incineration / sterile destruction of the bees, frames and all hive parts (excepting roofs in some cases) is mandatory for AFB infections.  For both foul broods, apiaries are set at standstill and all colonies inspected for further outbreaks of disease after 2 brood cycles - if all hives are clear, the standstill is lifted, otherwise, the whole process is repeated for hives with active infections and testing repeated after another six weeks.  For both AFB and EFB, notification to the relevant authority is a legal requirement in the UK (and probably the EUâ¦ however, many EU countries have a more "relaxed" attitude to these infectionsâ¦ and consequently higher infection rates!)
